Theory of Operation
*******************


 @{" Incentive for telnetd.device " Link "Incentive for telnetd.device"}          Why is @{b}telnetd.device@{ub} needed?
 @{" The telnet protocol " Link "The telnet protocol"}                   The network protocol @{b}telnetd.device@{ub}
                                           supports.
 @{" How telnetd.device works " Link "How telnetd.device works"}              The basic premise @{b}telnetd.device@{ub}
                                           operates under.


@EndNode

@Node "Incentive for telnetd.device" "telnetd_device.guide/Incentive for telnetd.device"
@Next "The telnet protocol"
@Toc "Theory of Operation"

Incentive for @{b}telnetd.device@{ub}
============================

   Networking is becoming more and more popular on the Amiga.  Thus,
people are now looking for ways to make their Amigas more accessable to
others on a network.  One common desire expressed many times on Usenet
is for a way to allow people on the net to connect into their bulletin
board system (BBS), for example.  Unfortunately, most BBS software is
written to talk only to modems and generally lacks support for network
protocols.  @{b}telnetd.device@{ub} was written to allow people to connect into
an Amiga running a serial-aware application from the net.


@EndNode

@Node "The telnet protocol" "telnetd_device.guide/The telnet protocol"
@Next "How telnetd.device works"
@Prev "Incentive for telnetd.device"
@Toc "Theory of Operation"

The @{b}telnet@{ub} protocol
===================

   In the world of TCP/IP, there are two main protocols widely used to
log into other machines on a network.  These are @{b}rlogin@{ub} and @{b}telnet@{ub}.
Most platforms with a TCP/IP stack support these protocols.
@{b}telnetd.device@{ub} was originally written to accept @{b}telnet@{ub} connections.  It
now knows how to accept @{b}rlogin@{ub} connections as well.


@EndNode

@Node "How telnetd.device works" "telnetd_device.guide/How telnetd.device works"
@Prev "The telnet protocol"
@Toc "Theory of Operation"

How @{b}telnetd.device@{ub} works
========================

   @{b}telnetd.device@{ub} is written to look like the standard Amiga
@{b}serial.device@{ub}.  @{b}serial.device@{ub} is the driver which serial applications
use to actually talk to the serial hardware.  It provides a high level
abstraction from the hardware, simplifying the application's job of
handling serial data.  Because of this abstraction, it is possible to
write @{b}serial.device@{ub} look-a-likes that talk to something other than the
Amiga's build in serial hardware.  Expansion serial boards for the
Amiga, such as Commodore's A2232 multi-port io board or GVP's
ioExternder board, are examples of the use of @{b}serial.device@{ub} clones to
talk to expansion serial hardware.

   By looking like @{b}serial.device@{ub}, @{b}telnetd.device@{ub} can be used by serial
applications.  However, looking like @{b}serial.device@{ub} is not enough.  Most
BBS programs, for example, assume that they are talking to a modem, and
look for certain messages generated by modems to indicate a call coming
in, etc.  Thus, @{b}telnetd.device@{ub} also emulates a Hayes compatible modem
to a limited degree.

   In conclusion, by telling serial applications (such as BBSs) to use
@{b}telnetd.device@{ub} instead of @{b}serial.device@{ub}, it is possible for the
application to receive @{b}telnet@{ub} connections.


@EndNode

